

What does a successful interaction look like?
Users should have a profile where they can identify as a pet or human. From there, they can post jobs and hire others. There should be a rating and comment system, searchable and filterable job listings, and a scheduling system to prevent double-booking.

Should owners have extra permissions compared to pet accounts?
Yes, owners should have an override or admin role over their pet accounts.

What should communication look like?
Communication should stay within the platform through a built-in messaging system. Personal contact info should never be exposed.

Website or mobile app?
A website is preferred since not all users will have smartphones. A mobile-friendly version is a stretch goal but not required. The minimum expectation is a functional HTML, CSS, and JavaScript site.

How do shelter animals get profiles?
A human account can manage multiple pet profiles. Volunteers or shelter staff handle scheduling on the animals behalf. There is no limit on how many pets one account can oversee.

Are there skill requirements to offer a service?
No formal validation. The platform should be inclusive and non-discriminatory. The review and ranking system acts as the natural quality filter. A badge or certificate system for top providers would be a welcome addition.

What about gamification?
Every five completed tasks earns a point, contributing to a leaderboard. This is more of a phase two feature but is something the client is enthusiastic about.

What should be on user profiles?
Name, species, photo, avatar, skills, specialties, pronouns, availability schedule, ratings, and reviews. Achievement-style taglines are also desired, where completing certain milestones earns a displayable title.

How should the review system work?
Only verified users who completed a transaction can leave a review. A code exchange between client and provider after job completion is the suggested verification method.

What security and verification features are needed?
At minimum, a login page with username and password and a password reset option. Two-factor authentication and a secure database are also desired. Credit card verification is a bonus if feasible.

Two-way rating system?
The client is open to it, similar to how Uber handles mutual ratings between drivers and riders.

Cap on number of pets per account?
No cap. Some shelters may manage hundreds of animals at a time.

Should shelters have a special account type?
Yes. Shelters should be a third user type alongside pets and humans. They should have special badges like "Cruelty Free" or "Certified Humane," along with adoption scheduling features and the ability to answer questions about individual animals.

Most important feature overall?
The ability for animals to contact each other through a direct messaging system or forum. This is the top priority.

Who is the design priority?
The animals. All other user types exist to support them, so the animal experience should be at the center of every design decision.

Can multiple pets join one job or session?
Yes. For example, a user should be able to hire five goats for a single lawn job. This was not originally considered but is strongly welcomed.

Minimum qualifications to offer a service?
None. The system relies on trust and reviews. Shelter super users can vouch for specific pets, and optional credibility features like skill photos or course badges could be explored as a stretch goal.

Proximity vs. preferences when matching?
Both, through a toggle. The default should be distance first, with preference-based filters available on top of that.

Predefined categories or user-created?
Predefined only. User-created categories lead to typos and search inconsistencies, making the platform harder to manage.

Group accounts and owner override?
Group or family accounts are supported. A two-way verification for owner overrides is ideal, where the pet account receives a notification to approve changes. If that is too complex, defaulting to the owner always having final say is acceptable.

How should payments work?
Payments should be flexible. Non-traditional options like toys and treats should be supported alongside standard methods. Payment type is negotiated between users, similar to Facebook Marketplace, and largely operates on an honor system.

How should job listings be displayed?
Visually appealing with plenty of graphics. The specific layout is up to the developers, but a plain text-based interface is not acceptable. The more attractive, the better.

How should location and privacy be handled?
Only general location info like a zip code should be visible publicly. Full address details stay private and are only shared between users once they are in direct contact, similar to how Airbnb handles it.

Can stray animals use the platform?
Yes, stray animals should be able to take on jobs as well.

